{"cursor":"2072","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox Kibbutz\n| name = Beit Arif foundation = 1949 founded_by = Bulgarian immigrants region =\n| council = Hevel Modi'in industry = affiliation = Moshavim Movement pushpin_map\n| = Israel center ta | pushpin_mapsize = 250 latd = 31|latm = 59|lats =\n| 40.92|latNS = N longd = 34|longm = 55|longs = 59.88|longEW = E website =\n}}\n\n'Beit Arif' (, lit. House of Cloud) is a moshav in central Israel. Located near\nShoham, it falls under the jurisdiction of Hevel Modi'in Regional Council. In\n2006 it had a population of 724.\n\nThe moshav was founded in 1949 by immigrants from Bulgaria on the ruins of the\nabandoned Arab village of Dayr Tarif. Carta's Official Guide to Israel and\nComplete Gazetteer to all Sites in the Holy Land. (3rd edition 1993) Jerusalem,\nCarta, p.108, ISBN 965-220-186-3 (English) It has originally named\n'Ahlama' () (Exodus 28:19), one of the 12 stones in the Hoshen, the sacred\nbreastplate worn by a Jewish high priest (two other nearby settlements, Bareket,\nShoham and Nofekh, are also named after such stones).\n\nIn the early 1950s some immigrants from Yemen arrived in the area, and built\nhomes around half a kilometre away. After disagreements between the two groups,\nthe original residents left and moved to Ginaton (a moshav also founded by\nBulgarian immigrants) in 1953. Place Names in Israel. A Compendium of Place\nNames in Israel compiled from various sources. Translated from Hebrew, Jerusalem\n1962 (Israel Prime Minsterâs Office. The Israeli Program for Scientific\nTranslations) p.27-28 (Location of the book: Ben Zvi Institute Library, 12\nAbarbanel St., Jerusalem; in the online-catalogue:\n[http://www.ybz.org.il/?CategoryID=157])\n","linknr":140,"url":"Beit_Arif","recorded":1374861157,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Beit_Arif&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Beit_Arif&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/